pr_body:
I encountered an issue when using the context to walk a remote windows machine.

On some folders, for example `smb://__foo__/C$/Users/__bar__/AppData/Local/Temporary Internet Files` I would get an `smbc.PermissionError`.

As long as the process lived, the internal TCP connection used by the smbclient stayed alive,
Although the context was long out of the scope (even tried **del** and **gcd.collect()**).

Digging in the code, seems the problem were dangling references that were not handled.

```c
static PyObject *
Context_opendir (Context *self, PyObject *args)
{
  PyObject *largs, *lkwlist;
  PyObject *uri;
  PyObject *dir;

  debugprintf ("%p -> Context_opendir()\n", self->context);
  if (!PyArg_ParseTuple (args, "O", &uri))
    {
      debugprintf ("%p <- Context_opendir() EXCEPTION\n", self->context);
      return NULL;
    }

  largs = Py_BuildValue ("()");
  lkwlist = PyDict_New ();
  PyDict_SetItemString (lkwlist, "context", (PyObject *) self);
  PyDict_SetItemString (lkwlist, "uri", uri);
  dir = smbc_DirType.tp_new (&smbc_DirType, largs, lkwlist);
  if (smbc_DirType.tp_init (dir, largs, lkwlist) < 0)
    {
       // -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
       // An Excpetion occured, but largs and lkwlist are still referenced
       // -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
      smbc_DirType.tp_dealloc (dir);
      debugprintf ("%p <- Context_opendir() EXCEPTION\n", self->context);
      return NULL;
    }

  // -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  // Here are the references which are not DECREFed if an exception occurs
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Py_DECREF (largs);
  Py_DECREF (lkwlist);
  debugprintf ("%p <- Context_opendir() = Dir\n", self->context);
  return dir;
}
```

This file is in /venv/ folder, which is in .gitignore. I am not sure how to deal with this. Shall I just add the file like this? I basically only comment out line 113.

Let me know! Thanks!
@percyliang

@apinkney97 It seems that this is caused within `_split_by_common_seq()`.  The problem is that it sticks with the latest matched "sequence". Thus, it skips 1 and 2 and in our case produces: `[ [(0, 2), None], [None, (1, 4)] ]`. If we instead start from our first match (which is 1) it should produce: `[[None, (0, 1)], [[None, (2, 3)], [(2, 3), None]]]` which, as it turns out, plays well with the rest of the logic.

I think my update fixes the issue, however optimization with move does not work in this particular case. So, I have added a temporary workaround until I investigate further.

@stefankoegl Test run fine on my setup, but please do make sure that I am not missing something.

Trying to close #2975.

@takluyver I did not go with ``document.execCommand`` because it does not allow you to set a mime-types like html, json, etc. (or I couldn't find a way to do that anyway) and I see you need that.

Let me know if these changes are okay.

Please note I have not thoroughly tested this PR yet so it probably shouldn't be merged until I've finished doing so but I'd like those interested to give it a try early on so we can weed out any issues. So far it seems to be working for me.

@kfriedberger I think you'll be interested in these changes. Note that in the build directory with the CMake build ``libz3java.so`` has the ``rpath`` set automatically so if ``libz3java.so`` is in your library search path ``libz3.so`` will be found automatically so there is no need for #537 if you just use the CMake build system once this PR is merged.

@jirislaby @arrowd I know you maintain packages for Z3 so feel free to give this PR a test. I'm not sure if I've exposed enough options to give the control packagers need.
